text: Well we have the Black Pearl out of a bottle! Which I am really excited about! We have Jack covered in ectoplasm... And We have the Flying Dutchman back along with Will Turner who seems to be turning into fishpeople, which means he broke the promise of ferrying souls to the next world just like Davy Jones...  Which leads me to think that Ellizabeth died somehow and Turner grew bitter and sad abbandoning his duty, which might be an interesting story line as Henry (Turner) his son might try to fix that. :) And damn that ship of Salazar at 0:27 is epic, really can't wait to see this.  Which I also noticed that the ship come is different stages of decomposition, sometimes it looks like a fine normal ship with white sails and a eagle like print on it like at 0:24 and at 0:34 and other times it looks like a decomposed ghost ship like at 0:27 Also Salazar really reminds me what Beckett and Jones did at the beginning of At Worlds End, exterminate all pirates, but in this case to search for Sparrow. And why the heck is Barbossa still wearing his royal navy outfit, he got his pirate outfit back at the end of On Stranger Tides.... Also really wonder what ship it is at the beginning, it's not the Dying Gull, but the deck is identical to the Black Pearl, only the sails are white...  I also wonder what kind of character David Wenham will play, haven't seen much of him in promotional or set images.

text: My thoughts on the Pirates movies...  I remember seeing the first when it was in theaters. I didn't expect much and was pleasantly surprised. Great movie.  The second one was fun to see in theaters with my camp. I'd be lying if I could understand it all but the comedy was great.   I didn't see the third one in theaters. I rented it from Netflix and was disappointed. It was way too long, hard to understand and just not as fun.  Maybe one or two laughs. The only fun part for me was seeing Keith Richards as Jack Sparrow's father. He was great.   The fourth one (which I did see in theaters) was worse- although there were parts of it that I liked a little more than the third one. Still- unmemorable.   I really don't know if I want to see the fifth. Maybe I'll rent it. It depends.

text: This movie should have been awesome. It was advertised as being epic and dark, but it was just a comedy movie, and nothing freaking made sense. The big sacrifice at the end, Will's curse at the end, the wedding scene, how Jack got the compass, none of it made sense! And to make it all worse, the directors thought it'd be hilarious to throw in some cartoon sound effects during the slapstick moments (nearly the whole movie was slapstick). The movie couldn't take itself seriously for one scene, even after the big sacrifice they cut to Jack the Monkey doing something cute. There were some good things, like David Wenham, Salazar, Carina, Barbossa, and Will, but that was really it. Overall it felt like it was in a different universe, the tone didn't match the other four movies at all, and I'm so disappointed in the directors and writers.

text: Sometimes in winter, when it's cold, I think back to Pirates of the Carribbean: The Curse of The Black Pearl, when Will drops the 882nd gold medallion into the chest with his blood on it.  At the time that this harrowing curse is, as result, lifted, Captain Barbosa, forced to bear the curse of undeath, is fatally shot. His dying words are as is, "I feel...cold."  It could be said this statement underplays death, and ones response to it. At this brief moment however Captain Barbosa might feel once more, whether it be the wind on his face, or the spray of the sea. And although as humans, before birth, we may not consider ourselves as being dead, I like to think that we were. That we were dead like Captain Barbosa, and his crew of scoundrels. Perhaps then we would long for the cold of the sea, or the chill of the night that we so quickly regret. Perhaps then we would be thankful to simply, feel.
